# {{lb|en|uncountable}} The spectral composition of visible light.
#: {{ux|en|Humans and birds can perceive '''colour'''.}}
#: {{syn|en|blee|q1=archaic}}
# A subset thereof:
## {{lb|en|countable}} A particular set of visible spectral compositions, perceived or named as a class.
##: {{ux|en|Most languages have names for the '''colours''' black, white, red, and green.}}
##: {{syn|en|hue|blee|q2=archaic}}
##* {{RQ:Maxwell Mirror and the Lamp|chapter=5|passage=Here, in the transept and choir, where the service was being held, one was conscious every moment of an increasing brightness; '''colours''' glowing vividly beneath the circular chandeliers, and the rows of small lights on the choristers' desks flashed and sparkled in front of the boys' faces, deep linen collars, and red neckbands.}}
## {{lb|en|uncountable}} [[hue|Hue]] as opposed to [[achromatic]] colours (black, white and greys).
##: {{ux|en|He referred to the white flag as one "drained of all '''colour'''".}}
##: {{syn|en|hue|shade|blee|q3=archaic}}
## These hues as used in [[colour television]] or films, colour photographs, etc (as opposed to the shades of grey used in black-and-white television).
##: {{ux|en|This film is broadcast in '''colour'''. &nbsp;Most people dream in '''colour''', but some dream in black and white.}}
##: {{syn|en|colour television}}
## {{lb|en|heraldry}} Any of the standard dark [[tincture]]s used in a [[coat of arms]], including [[azure]], [[gules]], [[sable]], and [[vert]].
##: {{cot|en|metal|stain}}
# A [[paint]].
#: ''The artist took out her '''colours''' and began work on a landscape.''
# {{lb|en|uncountable}} Human skin tone, especially as an indicator of race or [[ethnicity]].
#: {{ux|en|'''Colour''' has been a sensitive issue in many societies.}}
#: {{syn|en|complexion|ethnicity|race}}
# {{lb|en|medicine}} Skin colour, noted as normal, [[jaundiced]], [[cyanotic]], [[flush]], [[mottled]], [[pale]], or [[ashen]] as part of the [[skin signs]] assessment.
# A [[flushed]] appearance of blood in the face; redness of complexion.
#* '''1864''', Sir Henry Stewart Cunningham, ''Late Laurels'' (volumes 1-2, page 117)
#*: {{...}} her very embarrassment wore a graceful air; her high '''colour''' had softened down to a warm, delicate tint; and her dress, which looked beautifully new and fresh, was in good taste, and showed her off to advantage.
# {{senseid|en|detail}} {{lb|en|figuratively}} Richness of expression; detail or flavour that is likely to generate interest or enjoyment.
#: {{ux|en|There is a great deal of '''colour''' in his writing.}}
#: {{ux|en|a bit of local '''colour'''}}
#* {{RQ:Vance Nobody|I}}
#*: Three chairs of the steamer type, all maimed, comprised the furniture of this roof-garden, with (by way of local '''colour''') on one of the copings a row of four red clay flower-pots filled with sun-baked dust{{nb...}}.
#: {{ux|en|Could you give me some '''colour''' with regards to which products made up the mix of revenue for this quarter?}}
# A [[standard]], [[flag]], or [[insignia]]:
## {{lb|en|in the plural}} A [[standard]] or [[banner]].
##: {{ux|en|The loss of their '''colours''' destroyed the regiment's morale.}}
##: {{syn|en|banner|standard}}
## {{lb|en|in the plural}} The flag of a nation or team.
##: {{ux|en|The '''colours''' were raised over the new territory.}}
##* {{quote-book|en|page=7|chapter=[[:s:Treaty of friendship and commerce between Great Britain and Siam/Treaty|Treaty signed April 18, 1855; ratified April 5, 1856]]|title=Treaty of friendship and commerce between Great Britain and Siam|year=1856|publisher=J. H. Chandler|location=Bangkok|text=The arrival of the British Consul at Bangkok shall not take place before the ratification of this Treaty, nor until ten vessels owned by British subjects, sailing under British '''colours''' and with British papers, shall have entered the port of Bangkok for purposes of trade, subsequent to the signing of this Treaty.}}
## {{lb|en|in the plural}} Gang insignia.
##: {{ux|en|Both of the perpetrators were wearing '''colours'''.}}
# {{lb|en|in the plural}} An award for sporting achievement, particularly within a school or university.
#: {{ux|en|He was awarded '''colours''' for his football.}}
# {{lb|en|military|in the plural}} The morning ceremony of raising the flag.
# {{lb|en|physics}} A property of [[quark]]s, with three values called red, green, and blue, which they can [[exchange]] by passing [[gluon]]s; [[colour charge]].
# {{lb|en|finance|uncountable}} A [[third-order]] measure of [[derivative]] price sensitivity, expressed as the rate of change of [[gamma]] with respect to time, or equivalently the rate of change of [[charm]] with respect to changes in the [[underlying]] [[asset]] [[price]].
# {{lb|en|typography}} The relative [[lightness]] or [[darkness]] of a mass of written or printed [[text]] on a page. (See {{pedia|type colour}})
# {{lb|en|snooker}} Any of the colored balls excluding the [[red]]s.
# A [[front]] or [[façade]]; an [[ostensible]] truth actually false; [[pretext]].
#* '''2011''', David Baldacci, ''The Collectors''
#*: At the far end of the continuum, Roger Seagraves collected personal items from people he'd murdered, or assassinated rather, since he'd done it under the '''colour''' of serving his country.
# An appearance of right or authority; [[colour of law]].
#: {{ux|en|Under '''colour''' of law, he managed to bilk taxpayers of millions of dollars.}}
#* '''1882''', ''The Ohio Law Journal'' (volume 2, page 396)
#*: The only thing which this defendant is accused of doing is that he excluded this boy from the school, and he did it under the '''colour''' of the statute relating to the subject, and did it because he was a coloured boy.

